name: agent-safe
audience: public
description: >
  Authorization policy language for AI agents. SPL (Safe Policy Language)
  evaluates in ~2μs with zero runtime dependencies. Six SDK implementations
  (TypeScript, Go, Python, Rust, Java, C#) with Ed25519 signing, Merkle
  proofs, and hash-chain offline budgets.

domains:
  - authorization
  - policy-language
  - cryptographic-tokens
  - multi-language-SDK
  - AI-agent-safety

voice:
  tone: precise, security-first, minimal
  principles:
    - Authorization lives in the token, not a policy server
    - Zero runtime dependencies in core evaluators
    - Cross-SDK consistency is a security property
    - Fail closed on all crypto operations
  anti-patterns:
    - Adding runtime dependencies to core evaluators
    - Diverging behavior across SDKs
    - Trusting unsigned tokens
    - Policy evaluation with side effects

standards:
  code_review:
    - All 6 SDKs must produce identical results for shared test vectors
    - Crypto operations fail closed (no fallback to insecure)
    - Gas metering enforced (max 10k ops)
    - Full-envelope signing (policy + sealed + expires + merkle_root + hash_chain_commitment)
  documentation:
    - SPEC.md is the authoritative reference
    - Cross-SDK test vectors in examples/crypto/
  communication:
    - Lead with the security property being enforced

connects_to:
  - signet
  - kindex
